ent, England":"Lamberhurst, Kent, England","Arundel, Sussex, England":"Arundel, Sussex, England","Lamberhurst, Sussex, England":"Lamberhurst, Sussex, England","England":"England","Hockerton, Nottinghamshire, England":"Hockerton, Nottinghamshire, England"},"en":{"1272–1360":"1272–1360","–Male":"Deceased","1282–Female":"1282–Deceased","1296–Male":"1296–Deceased","1303–1353":"1303–1353","1240–1271":"1240–1271","1247–1280":"1247–1280","1296":"1296","1240":"1240","1272":"1272","1360":"1360","1271":"1271","1282":"1282","1280":"1280","1290":"1290","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1303":"1303","10 August 1280":"10 August 1280","1247":"1247","about 1303":"about 1303","1453":"1453","1353":"1353","about 1295":"about 1295","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Lamberhurst, Kent, England":"Lamberhurst, Kent, England","Arundel, Sussex, England":"Arundel, Sussex, England","Lamberhurst, Sussex, England":"Lamberhurst, Sussex, England","England":"England","Hockerton, Nottinghamshire, England":"Hockerton, Nottinghamshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Waller","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: occupational name from Middle English <i>waler</i>, <i>waliere</i>, <i>walour</i>, <i>waller</i> ‘builder of walls, mason’.","English: in Sussex, perhaps a topographic name for someone who lived by a prominent wall.","English: topographic name for someone who lived by a spring, stream, or man-made well, from Middle English <i>waller</i>, a derivative of Middle English <i>walle</i>, Old English <i>wælle</i>, <i>wælle</i>. It is a West Midlands dialect form of   Weller  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Wallar","meanings":["English: variant of   Waller  ."]},{"name":"Weller","meanings":["English (Surrey, Sussex, and Kent): topographic name for someone who lived by a spring, stream, or man-made well, from Middle English <i>weller</i>, <i>willer</i>, an agent derivative of Middle English <i>welle</i> (in southern England) and <i>wille</i> (in south western England), from Old English <i>wella</i>, <i>well(e)</i>, <i>wiella</i>, <i>wielle</i>, <i>willa</i>, <i>wyll(a)</i>, <i>wylle</i>. This type of name, a topographic term + <i>-er</i>, is particularly typical of Sussex and its neigbouring counties.","English: occupational name for someone who casts metal or who boils salt, from Middle English <i>weller</i>, <i>willer</i>, a derivative with <i>-er</i> of Old English <i>wellan</i>, <i>wiellan</i> ‘to boil’. Compare 5 below.","North German: variant of   Welle  , cognate with 1 above."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705190,"age":18,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705191,"age":43,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705192,"age":56,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705193,"age":65,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Baron Thomas Waller I was born in 1272, in Hockerton, Nottinghamshire, England, his father, Henry de Waller, was 32 and his mother, Alicia de Mortimer, was 25. He married Baroness Ann Keats about 1295, in England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. He died in 1360, in Lamberhurst, Kent, England, at the age of 88."},"et":{"1272–1360":"1272–1360","–Male":"Surnud","1282–Female":"1282–Surnud","1296–Male":"1296–Surnud","1303–1353":"1303–1353","1240–1271":"1240–1271","1247–1280":"1247–1280","1296":"1296","1240":"1240","1272":"1272","1360":"1360","1271":"1271","1282":"1282","1280":"1280","1290":"1290","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1303":"1303","10 August 1280":"10. august 1280","1247":"1247","about 1303":"umbes 1303","1453":"1453","1353":"1353","about 1295":"umbes 1295","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Lamberhurst, Kent, England":"Lamberhurst, Kent, England","Arundel, Sussex, England":"Arundel, Sussex, England","Lamberhurst, Sussex, England":"Lamberhurst, Sussex, England","England":"England","Hockerton, Nottinghamshire, England":"Hockerton, Nottinghamshire, England"},"fi":{"1272–1360":"1272–1360","–Male":"Kuollut","1282–Female":"1282–Kuollut","1296–Male":"1296–Kuollut","1303–1353":"1303–1353","1240–1271":"1240–1271","1247–1280":"1247–1280","1296":"1296","1240":"1240","1272":"1272","1360":"1360","1271":"1271","1282":"1282","1280":"1280","1290":"1290","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1303":"1303","10 August 1280":"10. elokuuta 1280","1247":"1247","about 1303":"noin 1303","1453":"1453","1353":"1353","about 1295":"noin 1295","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Lamberhurst, Kent, England":"Lamberhurst, Kent, Englan